Tetragon eBPF policy deployment (Tier 3 runtime isolation)
============================================================

Overview
--------
Tier 3 adds eBPF-level syscall enforcement via Tetragon (cilium/tetragon).
The Python builder in tessera.runtime.tetragon generates a ``TracingPolicy``
YAML; this directory contains a ready-to-apply reference policy and a Helm
values overlay for the Tetragon chart.

Prerequisites
-------------
- Kubernetes cluster with Tetragon installed:
    helm repo add cilium https://helm.cilium.io
    helm install tetragon cilium/tetragon -n kube-system -f tetragon-values.yaml
- Cilium CNI installed (required for the companion CiliumNetworkPolicy in ../cilium/).
- Linux kernel >= 5.10 on all nodes (eBPF CO-RE required).

Files in this directory
-----------------------
  tessera-tracing-policy.yaml   Reference TracingPolicy restricting tcp_connect
                                to the approved DNS + egress CIDRs for tessera pods.
  tetragon-values.yaml          Helm values overlay enabling the btf, export, and
                                monitor features needed by this policy.

Applying the policy
-------------------
  kubectl apply -f tessera-tracing-policy.yaml

Verify Tetragon is enforcing by checking its export log:
  kubectl logs -n kube-system -l app.kubernetes.io/name=tetragon -c export-stdout | \
    grep "tessera-egress-policy"

Helm install with overlay
-------------------------
  helm upgrade tetragon cilium/tetragon \
    -n kube-system \
    -f tetragon-values.yaml

Security notes
--------------
- The TracingPolicy uses a Sigkill action on deny. This terminates the offending
  process immediately. Tune to Override (return EPERM) if hard termination is
  too disruptive for your workload.
- Policies are cluster-scoped by default. Namespace-scoped policies require
  Tetragon >= 1.1 with the namespaced CRD variant.
- Tetragon itself must run with elevated capabilities (CAP_BPF, CAP_PERFMON).
  The daemonset pods are privileged; do not weaken this without testing.
